=== D === {| class="wikitable" !Dacian name !Possible etymology !Attestation !Notes |- |Dablosa | |He is attested at [[Mons Claudianus]](O. Claud. II 402 and 403).{{sfn|Dana|2003|p=174}} | |- |Dadas | |Ostracon of Dacian cavalry recruited after the Roman conquest and stationed in East Egypt {{sfn|Dana|2003|p=174}} | |- |Dadazi | |Ostracon of Dacian cavalry recruited after the Roman conquest and stationed in East Egypt {{sfn|Dana|2003|p=174}} | |- |Daizus | |Thraco-Getian name Daizus Comozoi, interfectus a Castabocis.{{sfn|Protase|2001|p=299}} Daizus Comozoi is a "Royal" Dacian name found also with Thracians from south of the Danube.{{sfn|Petolescu|1985|p=646}} | |- |Damanais | |Damanais attested at [[Mons Claudianus]] as the father of the Dacian soldier Dida from Krokodilo.{{sfn|Dana|2003|p=175}} | |- |[[Dapyx]] | |Dacian king.{{sfn|Tomaschek|1883|p=404}} | |- |Danillo | |Roman Legionnaire | |- |Dardanos |‘Darda-‘ appears as both Daco-Mysian and Thracian.{{sfn|Hamp|1966|p=108}} | | |- |Dardiolai | |Ostracon of Dacian cavalry recruited after the Roman conquest and stationed in East Egypt {{sfn|Dana|2003|p=175}} | |- |[[Decaeneus]] |"The one who knows" (''dak'', ''dek'' cf [[Sanskrit]] ''dasa'') or "The Dacian" {{sfn|Van Den Gheyn|1885|p=177}} |High priest and king of Dacians ([[Strabo]],{{sfn|Strabo|20 AD|loc=VII 3,5}} [[Dio Cassius]], [[Jordanes]]) | |- |Decibalus | |Chid of a soldier of [[cohors I Aelia Dacorum]]<ref name="plv"/> | |- |[[Decebalus]] |Dacian word ''balas '' /''balos'' is from PIE *bel 'strong, power' cf. Sanskrit ''bala'' "force" {{sfn|Russu|1969|p=163 and 109}} and Dece from PIE *dek ‘to take, to honor’{{sfn|Russu|1967|p=101}} Also, it had been suggested Decebalus "The force of the Dacians" {{sfn|Van Den Gheyn|1885|p=177}} |King of Dacians ([[Dio Cassius]]) |Originally named ''Diurpaneus'', after his victory against Romans he was called Decebalus ("The brave one")<ref name="Romanis REquote01">{{cite web |accessdate=2007-11-08 |url=http://www.roman-emperors.org/assobd.htm#t-inx |title=De Imperatoribus Romanis |work=An Online Encyclopedia of Roman Emperors |format=Assorted Imperial Battle Descriptions |quote= Battle of Sarmizegetusa (Sarmizegetuza), A.D. 105. During Trajan"s reign one of the most important Roman successes was the victory over the Dacians. The first important confrontation between the Romans and the Dacians took place in the year 87 and was initiated by Domitian. The [[praetorian prefect]] [[Cornelius Fuscus|Cornelius]] led five or six legions across the Danube on a bridge of ships and advanced towards [[Banat]] (in Romania). The Romans were surprised by a Dacian attack at Tapae (near the village of [[Bucova]], in Romania). Legion V Alaude was crushed and Cornelius Fuscus was killed. The victorious general was originally known as [[Diurpaneus]] (see Manea, p.109), but after this victory he was called Decebalus (the brave one).}}</ref> Many interpretations are possible for the PIE root ''*dek'' that is found also with the name Decaeneus{{sfn|Tomaschek|1883|p=405}} |- |Denzibalos | |Ostracon of Dacian cavalry recruited after the Roman conquest and stationed in East Egypt {{sfn|Dana|2003|p=175}} | |- |Denzibalus | |Attested in [[Britannia]] {{sfn|Dana|2003|p=175}} | |- |Dekinais | |Ostracon of Dacian cavalry recruited after the Roman conquest and stationed in East Egypt {{sfn|Dana|2003|p=175}} | |- |[[Dicomes]] | |king of Dacians {{sfn|Tomaschek|1883|p=404}} | |- |Dida | |Aelius Dida - Dacian [[centurion]] of [[cohors I Aelia Dacorum]] stationed in [[Britannia]].<ref name="plv"/> | |- |Dida(s) | |Dacian soldier from Krokodilo.{{sfn|Dana|2003|p=175}} | |- |[[Diegis]] |Diegis / Degis from *dhegh ‘ to burn’ {{sfn|Russu|1967|p=133}} |Dacian {{sfn|Tomaschek|1883|p=404}} | |- |Diengis | |Ostracon of Dacian cavalry recruited after the Roman conquest and stationed in East Egypt {{sfn|Dana|2003|p=185}} | |- |Dieri | |Ostracon of Dacian cavalry recruited after the Roman conquest and stationed in East Egypt {{sfn|Dana|2003|p=185}} | |- |Diernais | |Ostracon of Dacian cavalry recruited after the Roman conquest and stationed in East Egypt {{sfn|Dana|2003|p=185}} | |- |Diourdanos | |Ostracon of Dacian cavalry recruited after the Roman conquest and stationed in East Egypt {{sfn|Dana|2003|p=183}} | |- |[[Diurpaneus]] |"admired from distance" cf. Sanskrit ''durepanya''{{sfn|Tomaschek|1883|p=405}}{{sfn|Van Den Gheyn|1885|p=177}} |Name of the king of Dacians ([[Dio Cassius]]) He was renamed to Decebalus after victory over Romans. |It is a "Royal" Dacian name found also with Thracians from south of the Danube i.e. Dorpanas (IGB, II, 771) and Dyrpanais (Olbia).{{sfn|Petolescu|1985|p=646}} |- |Dourpokis | |Ostracon of Dacian cavalry recruited after the Roman conquest and stationed in East Egypt {{sfn|Dana|2003|p=183}} | |- |Dotos | |Ostracon of Dacian cavalry recruited after the Roman conquest and stationed in East Egypt {{sfn|Dana|2003|p=177}} | |- |Dotouzi | |Ostracon of Dacian cavalry recruited after the Roman conquest and stationed in East Egypt {{sfn|Dana|2003|p=177}} | |- |Drilgisa | |With the inscription CIL VI 1801 as Natopor's brother at Rome.{{sfn|Dana|2003|p=174}} |Note also the following names: Drigissa in Superior Moesia and Dia-giza, slave at Rome, CIL XV 2445.{{sfn|Dana|2003|p=174}} |- |[[Dromichaetes]], Dromichaeta | |Name of the king of Getae{{sfn|Tomaschek|1883|p=404}} It appears this is a Hellenised form {{sfn|Tomaschek|1883|p=404}} | |- |Duccidava | |Daughter of a dacian soldier mentioned in a [[Roman military diploma]] issued in 127 in [[Mauretania Caesariensis]] {{sfn|Dana|2006|pp=118-119}} | | |- |[[Duras (Dacian king)|Duras]] | |King of the Dacians between 69 AD - 87 AD ([[Jordanes]]) | |}
