{| class="wikitable sortable" !No !Dacian name !Etymology !Modern city/Location !Attestation !Notes |- |1 |[[Acidava]] (''Acidaua'') | |[[Enoşeşti]], [[Olt County]], Romania |[[Tabula Peutingeriana]]{{sfn|Tabula Peutingeriana|loc=Segmentum VIII}} | |- |2 |[[Amutria]] (''Amutrion'', ''Amutrium'', ''Admutrium'',{{sfn|Pippidi|1976|p=17}} ''Ad Mutrium'', ''Ad Mutriam'', {{lang-grc|Ἀμούτριον}}{{sfn|Nobbe|1845|p=10}}) | |Hypothetically located at one of the following sites in [[Oltenia]] (Southwestern Romania): * [[Valea Perilor, Gorj|Valea Perilor]], commune [[Cătunele]], Gorj County{{sfn|Diaconovich|1898|p=758}} * [[Motru]], [[Gorj County]]{{sfn|Schütte|1917|p=96}} * [[Gura Motrului]], commune [[Butoieşti]], [[Mehedinţi County]]{{sfn|Schütte|1917|p=96}} * [[Botoşeşti-Paia]], [[Dolj County]]{{sfn|Pippidi|1976|p=17}} |[[Ptolemy]]'s [[Geographia]], Tabula Peutingeriana{{sfn|Tabula Peutingeriana|loc=Segmentum VII}} | |- |3 |[[Apula]] (''Apulon'') | |Piatra Craivii, 20&nbsp;km North of [[Alba-Iulia]], [[Romania]] |Tabula Peutingeriana{{sfn|Tabula Peutingeriana|loc=Segmentum VIII}} |Apulum in Latin, see also [[Apuli]] |- |4 |[[Bersobis]] (''Berzobim'') | "White, shine" including birch-tree from root *bhereg > ber(e)z {{sfn|Parvan |1926|p=245}} Alternatively, it could be compared with [[Berzama]], place name from Thrace between [[Amhialos]] and [[Kabyle (ancient city)|Kabyle]] and [[Bactrian language|Bactrian]] Bareza ‘height’ {{sfn|Tomaschek|1883|p=402}} | Modern [[Berzovia]] village in [[Caraș-Severin County]], on the bank of river [[Bârzava River (Timiş)|Bârzava]], Romania |The sole surviving sentence from Trajan's campaign journal in the Latin grammar work of Priscian, Institutiones grammaticae {{sfn|Priscian|520|loc=VI 13}} | |- |5 |[[Napoca (ancient city)|Napoca]] (''Napuca'') |The following are the most important hypotheses regarding ''Napoca'''s etymology: * [[Dacian language|Dacian]] name having the same root "nap" (cf. ancient [[Armenian language|Armenian]] root "nap") with that of the Dacia's river Naparis attested by [[Herodotus]]. It has an augmentative suffix uk/ok i.e. over, great {{sfn|Tomaschek|1883|p=406}} * Name derived from that of the Dacianized [[Scythian]] tribe known as Napae <ref>Pârvan (1982) p.165 and p.82</ref> * Name probably akin to the indigenous ([[Thracian]]) element in [[Romanian language]], the word năpârcă 'viper' cf. [[Albanian language|Albanian]] nepërkë, nepërtkë <ref>Paliga (2006) 142</ref> * Name derived from the [[Ancient Greek]] term ''napos'' ({{lang|grc|νάπος}}) "timbered valley" * Name derived from the [[Proto-Indo-European language|Indo-European]] ''*snā-p-'' ([[Indogermanisches etymologisches Wörterbuch|Pokorny]] 971-2) "to flow, to swim, damp".{{sfn|Lukács|2005|p=14}} Independent of these hypotheses, scholars agree that the name of the settlement predates the [[Trajan's Dacian Wars|Roman conquest]] (AD 106).{{sfn|Lukács|2005|p=14}} |[[Cluj-Napoca]], Romania{{sfn|Bunbury|1879|p=516}} |Tabula Peutingeriana{{sfn|Tabula Peutingeriana|loc=Segmentum VIII}} {{sfn|Bunbury|1879|p=516}} | |- |}
